definition.en: The accessibility characteristics of an entity used by passengers such as a Stop Place.
Describes the usability of an entity for passengers with certain needs.
Characteristics of the accommodation available on a service.

usage.en: Eg First Class Couchette with Shower.

definition.en: An Organisation under which the responsibility of organising the transport service in a certain area is placed.
An Authority or an Operator.

usage.en: Abstract class, i.e. one of its subclasses Authority or Operator should be instantiated.

definition.en: Information on how to book a public transport service.
A type of day characterised by one or more properties which affect public transport operation.

usage.en: For example: weekday in school holidays.

definition.en: The assignment of operational characteristics, expressed by Day Types, to particular Operating Days within a Service Calendar.
An advertised destination of a specific Line or Journey Pattern, usually displayed on a head sign or at other on-board locations.
Variant of a given Destination Display, as needed for different media channels (electronic, printed, audio, mobile app, etc.).
States the relative direction of use of a Line, e.g. "North Bound", "South Bound", etc.
A set of Entities grouped together according to a purpose of grouping, e.g. grouping of stops known to the public by a common name.

Group of Lines can be used to define several kinds of PT networks and sub-networks: what is usually called a public transport network is in fact only a specific GroupOfLines and a Line may belong to several of them.
A time interval or a duration defining a headway period and characterizing Headway Journey Groups (e.g. every 10 min, every 4-6 min).
Travel from one place to another.
A part of a Vehicle Journey created according to a specific functional purpose, for instance in situations when vehicle coupling or separation occurs.
A set of two ore more JourneyParts of different VehicleJourneys, served simultaneously by the same Train by coupling individual vehicles.
The relative position in the train of a JourneyPart from a given stop onwards.

usage.en: May change in the course of the journey as train components are coupled and uncoupled.

definition.en: An ordered list of Scheduled Stop Points and Timing Points on a single Route, describing the pattern of working for public transport vehicles. A Journey Pattern may pass through the same Point more than once.
A grouping of Routes that is generally known to the public by a similar name or number.
Oriented spatial object of dimension 1 with view to the overall description of a Network, describing a connection between two Points.

A Link Sequence describes a path through a Network, such as a bus route. It can consist of an ordered set of Points in Sequence (referencing Points of a particular type) or Links in Sequence (referencing Links of a particular type).
A named grouping of Lines under which a Transport network is known.

Additional information for passengers that may help them in planning or executing
their trip.
The assignment of a Notice to an Entity.
A day of public transport operation of which the characteristics are defined within in a specific Service Calendar.

usage.en: An Operating Day may last more than 24 hours.

definition.en: A continuous interval of time between two Operating Days which will be used to define validity.
A company providing public transport services.
The maximum number of passengers that can travel with a Vehicle.
The allocation of a Scheduled Stop Point to a Stop Place.

usage.en: More details on this class in the application profile NETEX Belgium - Stop Places.

definition.en: A Passing Time associates a time with a Point in Journey Pattern.
A 0-dimensional node of the Network used for the spatial description of the Network. Points may be located by a Location in a given Locating System.
Each Point in Journey Pattern specifies the visit of a Service to a specific Point in a particular order within the pattern.
A Point in a Link Sequence indicating its order in that particular Link Sequence.
A Point on Route indicates the sequence of a Route Point within a Route. This intermediate object is required to allow a Route to go several times through the same RoutePoint.
Defines a uniform set of values to control appearances of an element (on a map, a schematic map, a paper or screen description, etc.).
A property which a day may possess, such as school holiday, weekday, summer, winter etc.
Ordered list of located Points defining one single path through the road (or rail) Network. A Route may pass through the same Point more than once.
An oriented link between two Route Points allowing the definition of a unique path through the Network. The same Route Link may be used in different Routes.
A Point used to define the shape of a Route through the Network. The same Point may be used in different Routes using a Point on Route.
A Point where passengers can board or alight from vehicles.
Collection of Day Types Assignments.
Describes the Facilities available onboard a service.

usage.en: Including the type of Accommodation (seating, couchettes, etc.).

definition.en: Vehicle Journey on which passengers will be allowed to board or alight from vehicles at stops.

The connection between two successive Scheduled Stop Points in a Service Journey. Since a Journey is always valid for a specific time (on a specific Day Type), each Service Journey Link has a specific departure and arrival time. Service Journey Links allow Route Planners to more easily calculate the shortest Routes.
Journey Pattern for a (passenger carrying) Service Journey.
Link between an ordered pair of Scheduled Stop Points.
A type of Place, such as a Stop Place, Point of Interest or Address, to which passengers may wish to travel.
A Stop Place represents a station, stop, port, airport or any physical point of access to the transport network.

usage.en: More details on this class in the application profile NETEX Belgium - Stop Places.

definition.en: Each Point inJourney Pattern specifies the visit of a Service to a specific Scheduled Stop Point in a particular order within the pattern.
A Zone used to define a zonal fare structure.

The PassingTimes that are the result of the scheduling process and to be published in a timetable are called TimeTabledPassingTimes. 

The TimeTabledPassingTimes are normally generated a long time before the day of operation and are valid over a long period of time (e.g. summer, winter timetable)
A period in a day, significant for some aspect of public transport, e.g. similar traffic conditions or fare category.
A Point against which the timing information necessary to build schedules may be recorded.
A Train is a vehicle composed of TrainElements in a certain order, i.e. of wagons assembled together and propelled by a locomotive or one of the wagons.
Specification of the order of TrainElements in a Train.
Elementary component of a Train.

usage.en: Eg a wagon, a locomotive).

definition.en: Provides the specification of codes assigned to particular VehicleJourneys when operated by Trains according to a functional purpose (passenger information, operation follow-up, etc.).
An alternative optimised representation of an Operating Period that uses a string of bits to indicate to which days with the period a specific DayType applies.

A VehicleJourney is the defined movement of a vehicle using a specified Journey Pattern on a particular Route. By virtue of being defined for a Day Type, a Vehicle Journey is a class of journeys that would take place at the same time on each day of a specified Day Type.
Vehicles may be classified using a Vehicle Type according to how they meet vehicle scheduling requirements as to capacity and on-board facilities (e.g. standard bus, double decker, etc.).

Curve with linear interpolation between the points. Each successive pair of points forms a line segment. The Line String has at least two points.

usage.en: A Curve is a 1-dimensional geometric object, defined as a sequence of points. The interpolation can take different forms (e.g. linear in the case of a Line String)

definition.en: A 0-dimensional geometric object that represents a particular location in a coordinate space. Has an x coordinate and a y coordinate. Can also have a z coordinate (height) and an m coordinate (distance along a curve).
Surface consisting of 1 outer boundary and 0 or more inner boundaries. Each inner boundary forms a hole in the polygon.

usage.en: The boundaries are so-called linear rings, that is, they are closed (non-self-intersecting) LineStrings. The outer boundary is distinguished from the inner boundary by the clockwise and counterclockwise directions in which the ring runs.

definition.en: Type of Organization.
Information used to uniquely identify an object.

usage.en: The basic principle here is that this string is assigned by an organization and that this is done according to a well-defined system.

definition.en: More readable representation of a structured Address with only the basic or combined data, intended for the use of an address as an attribute of another object or as a label.

usage.en: Eg as an attribute of a person or building or as a label on a letter or a map.

definition.en: Shape and position characteristics of an object.

usage.en: Describes these features using points, lines, polygons, and coordinates.

definition.en: A recognized organization, recognized in a broad sense or more specifically in a legal sense, with associated rights and obligations.

usage.en: Eg a company, a non-profit organization, a government body, a church community.

definition.en: A number of people organized into a community or other social, commercial, or political structure. The group has a common purpose or raison d'être that transcends its individual members and it can act as an agent. An organization often has a hierarchical structure.

usage.en: More details on this class in the W3C Organization Ontology.

definition.en: Organization with a legal status established by registration. This is more specific than a Formal Organization where this status can also be obtained in another way.

usage.en: In Belgium, like in many other countries, the following kinds Organizations must register: company, sole proprietorship, government body, foundation Upon registration, the Organization receives a company number and its details are entered in a central registry called Crossrads Bank for Enterprises (CBE). More details on this class in the Registered Organization Vocabulary.

definition.en: Information that makes it possible to refer in a structured and unique way to a building unit, a berth, a location or a plot on the basis of a municipality name, a street name, a house number and possibly a bus number and a postal code.

usage.en: The definition refers to Belgian Addresses. In other countries, an Address may refer to other geographical objects (not a building unit or parcel) or may consist of other designations (different from house number and bus number) or of components other than street name, municipality name or postal code. Foreign addresses can be exchanged using the Address Representation object. More detail on this class in the INSPRE Address specification.

definition.en: Indication of a quantity.

usage.en: In practice the primitive data types with which a quantity can be indicated, see xsd data types Float, Double, Decimal, Integer etc.

definition.en: Indication of the quantity of a particular characteristic of an object.

usage.en: For example, the height of an object, the weight, the temperature, etc. It concerns a characteristic that can be expressed numerically and in a certain unit. Qualitative indications such as high, low, etc. are therefore not included.

definition.en: Unit established by a standardizing organization.

usage.en: Datatype can be a URI or a TypedString. In the first case, reference is made to units published on the web, preferably those from qudt, eg http://qudt.org/vocab/unit/M for meter. In the case of a TypedString, preference is given to the UCUM codes, eg "km/h"^^http://w3id.org/lindt/custom_datatypes#ucumunit.
